<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-623  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 623.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Sept 10 1990 v36 n1826 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DEC to start cutting up to 6,000 jobs.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stedman, Craig.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>DEC begins a new workforce reduction program intended to cut up to6,000 jobs through a severance program that is much less generousthan one offered earlier in 1990.andP;  The earlier reductions ended inJun 1990 and cut 3,000 workers from the company; the new programwill be implemented at individual facilities on a one-by-one basisthrough Jun 1991, although most of the cuts are expected to bemade by Dec 1990.andP;  The program is voluntary, but DEC says specificjobs are being targeted for elimination, forcing workers in thosepositions to accept the severance deal or try to find anotherposition with the company.andP;  Employees who agree to leave receivebetween 13 and 77 weeks of pay, depending on their length ofemployment with the company; the previous program provided between44 and 104 weeks of pay.andP;  DEC reported its first-ever quarterlyloss in Jun 1990, and future quarters may also be unprofitable.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (layoffs).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     MinicomputersManufacturersLayoffFinancial StabilityComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>